<i>cofa</i> ‘shelter’ (see   Cove  ) or of a personal name <i>Cofa</i> (of uncertain origin) + Old English <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. This surname is also established in Ireland, where it is more probably a phonetic Anglicization of an Irish name. See sense 2.","Irish (Cork): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Coibhdheanaigh</b> or <b>Mac Coibhdheanaigh</b> ‘descendant’ or ‘son’ of <i>Coibhdheanach</i>, a personal name derived from the Irish word <i>coibhdhean</i> ‘(marauding) troop, raiding party’."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma de Coventry was born in 1165